[[File:Ninomiya-jinja (Funabashi) torii.JPG|thumb|250px|right|Torii]]'''Ninomiya Shrine'' (Ninomiya Shrine) is located in {{ill|lt=Chiba Prefecture|Q80011|WD=Q80011|1=Chiba Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Funabashi City|Q271417|WD=Q271417|1=Funabashi}} Miyama. In {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}{{ill|lt=Ronsha|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}, tell them {{ill|lt=Shimosa Province|Q1053695|WD=Q1053695|1=Shimōsa Province}}{{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|lt=Ninomiya|1=Ichinomiya}}. {{ill|lt=Modern company rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Old company rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. In ancient times, it was also called ``Miyama Myojin'' or ``Ninomiya Myojin''. </ref>.

=== Enshrined God ===
The enshrined deity is listed according to the shrine history book. 
* '''{{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Kenhaya Susano no Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}'''
* '''{{ill|lt=Kushinada Hime|Q505469|WD=Q505469|lt=Kushiinada Hime no Mikoto|1=Kushinadahime}}'''
* '''{{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Ōkuninushi no Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}'''
* '''{{ill|lt=Fujiwara Tokihira|Q2994735|WD=Q2994735|lt=Fujiwara Tokihira Mikoto|1=Fujiwara no Tokihira}}'''
:According to legend, when {{ill|lt=Fujiwara no Moritsune|Q11623227|WD=Q11623227|1=Fujiwara no Moritsune}}, who was demoted in 4th year ({{ill|lt=1180|Q19702|WD=Q19702|1=1180}}), settled in this area, he enshrined his ancestor, Fujiwara Tokihira, in his side hall. Since Tokihira is a political enemy of {{ill|lt=Michizane Sugawara|Q382005|WD=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}} (Tenjin), it is said that the parishioners of Tenjin did not visit the shrine <ref name="place name"/>.
* '''{{ill|lt=Emperor Nintoku|Q313119|WD=Q313119|lt=Daisaku no Mikoto|1=Emperor Nintoku}}'''
:{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|WD=Q3125096}} Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine, a nearby mukakusha, was {{ill|lt=together enshrined|Q11412524|WD=Q11412524|1=Co-Enshrinement}}.
* '''{{ill|lt=Emperor Ojin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|lt=Hondabetsu no Mikoto|1=Emperor Ōjin}}'''
:In the Meiji period, Setsusha and Awa Hachiman Shrine were enshrined together.

=== History ===
According to the shrine's legend, the <ref name="historical history book"> shrine history book was founded by the imperial order of {{ill|lt=Emperor Saga|Q316654|WD=Q316654|1=Emperor Saga}} during the {{ill|lt=Konin|Q1373070|WD=Q1373070|1=Kōnin (era)}} years ({{ill|lt=810|Q23819|WD=Q23819|1=810}} to {{ill|lt=824|Q30353|WD=Q30353|1=824}}). </ref>. Like place names, the name ``Miyama'' appeared to be ``Miyama'' in ancient times, and was attributed to our company. {{ill|lt=Miyama clan|Q11355183|WD=Q11355183|1=Miyama clan}} served as {{ill|lt=priests|Q11589454|WD=Q11589454|1=Shinkan (official)}} for generations. <ref> ``Chiba Prefecture place name'' Miyama Village. </ref>.``{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}'' from the middle of the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmeicho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shinmeicho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} states: Samukawa Shrine", but our company is said to be {{ill|lt=Ronsha|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}. It is also said that it was revered by the imperial court as {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|lt=Ninomiya|1=Ichinomiya}} of {{ill|lt=Shimosa Province|Q1053695|WD=Q1053695|1=Shimōsa Province}} (however, {{ill|lt=Tamazaki Shrine|Q11572538|WD=Q11572538|1=Tamasaki Shrine}} of {{ill|lt=Asahi City|Q637868|WD=Q637868|1=Asahi, Chiba}} is also called Ninomiya). It is unknown when it began to be called Ninomiya Shrine, but (Japan)|Q1327472|Inuigen}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1303|Q5614|WD=Q5614|1=1303}}) The temple bell (stored in Shohoin, Narita City) says ``Soshu Ninomiya Shadan'', which suggests that this name already existed in the {{ill|lt=Kamakura period|Q236205|WD=Q236205|1=Kamakura period}}.{{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} In 19 years ({{ill|lt=1591|Q6766|WD=Q6766|1=1591}}), {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Ieyasu|Q171977|WD=Q171977|1=Tokugawa Ieyasu}} gave {{ill|lt=shuinji/black seals|Q11521520|WD=Q11521520|lt=shuinji|1=shuinchi and kokuinchi}} 10 koku and <ref name="Place name"/>, {{ill|lt=Edo Shogunate|Q205662|WD=Q205662|1=Tokugawa shogunate}}The shogun made donations many times. {{ill|lt=Ansei|Q1327259|WD=Q1327259|1=Ansei}}It is introduced in ``Narita Pilgrimage Record'' published in 1858 along with an illustration of ``Miyama Myo Shrine''.

After entering {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}, it was ranked as {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} in {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}. In 1910, Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine and Gensetsusha Awa Hachiman Shrine were enshrined together.

Since ancient times, "Shirenshita" (area of parishioners) has consisted of 21.3 villages (currently {{ill|lt=Funabashi City|Q271417|WD=Q271417|1=Funabashi}} eastern and northern areas, {{ill|lt=Narashino City|Q318047|WD=Q318047|1=Narashino}}, {{ja link|Yachiyo City|Q328651}}, {{ill|lt=Chiba City|Q170616|WD=Q170616|1=Chiba (city)}}), and its influence can still be seen today at annual festivals.

=== Precincts ===

=== Shrine building ===
The current shrine building was rebuilt during the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Yasunaga|1=UNKNOWN}} years ({{ill|lt=1772|Q7690|WD=Q7690|1=1772}} to {{ill|lt=1781|Q7719|WD=Q7719|1=1781}}). Both the main shrine and worship hall have copper plate roofs, but the main shrine was built in {{ill|lt=Taisho|Q329174|WD=Q329174|1=Taishō era}}11 ({{ill|lt=1922|Q2165|WD=Q2165|1=1922}})1 In October, the worship hall had its {{ill|lt=thatched roof|Q874531|WD=Q874531|1=Thatching}} roof replaced in Taisho 14 ({{ill|lt=1925|Q18107|WD=Q18107|1=1925}}). The floor plan of this shrine is {{ill|lt=Gongen-zukuri|Q3155268|WD=Q3155268|1=Ishi-no-ma-zukuri}}, which was popular during the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, but the floor height from {{ill|lt=haiden|Q3125745|WD=Q3125745|1=Haiden (Shinto)}} to {{ill|lt=haiden|Q3076699|WD=Q3076699|1=Heiden (Shinto)}} is the same. In addition, the {{ill|lt=eaves|Q11637472|WD=Q11637472|1=eaves}}'s {{ill|lt=kumimono|Q7814068|WD=Q7814068|1=Tokyō (architecture)}} and koshigumi were designed and constructed using the regular {{ill|lt=miya carpenter|Q65261787|WD=Q65261787|1=miyadaiku}} method of the time. In 1978 ({{ill|lt=1978|Q2483|WD=Q2483|1=1978}}) {{ill|lt=October 25|Q2954|WD=Q2954|1=October 25}}, it was designated as {{ill|lt=List of Funabashi City Designated Cultural Properties|Q11614137|WD=Q11614137|lt=Funabashi City's Tangible Cultural Properties|1=Funabashi City's Tangible Cultural Properties}}.

